Author-Name:    Dow, James
Author-Name:  Gorton, Gary
Title:   Noise Trading, Delegated Portfolio Management, and Economic Welfare. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 1024-50
Issue: 5
Volume: 105
Year: 1997
Month:  October 
Abstract:
  The authors consider a model of the stock market with delegated portfolio
 management. Portfolio managers try, but sometimes fail, to discover
 profitable trading opportunities. Although it is best not to trade in this
 case, their clients cannot distinguish 'actively doing nothing,' in this
 sense, from 'simply doing nothing.' The authors show that some portfolio
 managers trade even though they have no reason to prefer one asset to
 another (noise trade); the amount of such noise trade can be large
 compared to the amount of hedging volume; and, perhaps surprisingly, noise
 trade may be Pareto improving.   Copyright 1997 by the University of Chicago.
