Author-Name:    Diamond, Douglas W
Title:   Liquidity, Banks, and Markets. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 928-56
Issue: 5
Volume: 105
Year: 1997
Month:  October 
Abstract:
  This paper examines the roles of markets and banks when both are active,
 characterizing the effects of financial market development on the
 structure and market share of banks. Banks lower the cost of giving
 investors rapid access to their capital and improve the liquidity of
 markets by diverting demand for liquidity from markets. Increased
 participation in markets causes the banking sector to shrink, primarily
 through reduced holdings of long-term assets. In addition, increased
 participation leads to longer-maturity real and financial assets and a
 smaller gap between the maturity of financial and real assets.   Copyright 1997 by the University of Chicago.
